Thought_Process: This procedure is the Top Trading Cycles mechanism. Under TTC, reporting your true preference order is a dominant strategy: you cannot improve your final assignment by misreporting, given full information and fixed school priorities/quotas. Therefore, to maximize the chance of being placed as high as possible on your true preference list, you should submit your true ranking unchanged.

This procedure is the student-proposing Top Trading Cycles (TTC): each round, students point to their top remaining school and each school points to its highest-priority remaining student; any cycle is executed. In TTC, reporting true preferences is a dominant strategy for students, so misordering cannot improve my outcome. With truthful rankings, Round 1 pointers are: A->B, B->A, C->B, D->B, E->C; schools point: A->E, B->E, C->B, D->D, E->A. Cycles: (B,C) gives me School_B; (D) gives D School_B; (A,E,C) gives A->B, E->C, C->D. Thus my best achievable match is School_B, and truthful reporting attains it; any deviation cannot get me School_A (School_A’s top priority is Student_E and E can secure A via a cycle) and could only risk a worse assignment.

This procedure is the student-proposing Top Trading Cycles. Reporting true preferences is a dominant strategy: misordering can only cause you to apply to a less-preferred school earlier and potentially get locked into it via a cycle, while it cannot improve your outcome because cycles form based on schools’ top remaining priorities. With full information, the safest way to maximize your match on your true preference list is to submit it truthfully.

This mechanism is Top Trading Cycles. To maximize my outcome, I should report my true preferences because TTC is strategy-proof for students: misreporting cannot get me a better school than truthful reporting. Given others’ preferences and schools’ top priorities, the first cycle will be Student_E↔School_C, then Student_B↔School_A, then Student_C↔School_B, leaving me to be matched with School_D (since School_D points to me as its top remaining student). No alternative ordering can improve on this under TTC, so I submit my true list.

This procedure is the Top Trading Cycles mechanism. This procedure is Top Trading Cycles. If I rank School_B first (my true top choice), in Step 1 I apply to School_B. School_B’s top priority is Student_E, who applies to School_C. School_C’s top priority is Student_B, who applies to School_A. School_A’s top priority is Student_E, creating a loop (Student_E -> School_C -> Student_B -> School_A -> Student_E) that does not include me, so those seats are removed. In Step 2, the remaining schools are B, D, E; I then apply to School_B (still my highest remaining). Among remaining students, School_B’s top priority is Student_C, who applies to School_B as well, so Student_C gets B. In Step 3, remaining schools are D and E; I apply to School_E (my top among remaining) and School_E’s top priority among remaining students is me, so I get School_E. Any attempt to get School_C or School_A instead fails because those seats are taken in Step 1 regardless of my ranking, and ranking lower choices first would only risk ending up with School_D. Therefore, submitting my true order is optimal and yields the best achievable outcome (School_E).

This guarantees me School_E, which is better than School_D and is the best achievable given priorities (I cannot obtain B, C, or A because those schools prioritize other students above me in the relevant cycles).
